## 6. Compliance and Consent Design

The AI engine treats clinical compliance as a first-class schema concern.

### Mandatory Disclaimer Architecture

Every `ai_interpretations` record carries a `disclaimer` field. The `ai_branding_settings` table controls how this is presented per-tenant:

```sql
CREATE TABLE `ai_branding_settings` (
  `display_name`    varchar(191),  -- White-label AI name (e.g. "Lab Insights")
  `subtitle`        varchar(191),  -- Tagline shown to patients
  `disclaimer_text` text,          -- The mandatory non-diagnostic disclaimer
  `updated_by`      bigint         -- Admin who last changed this
);
```

A clinical lab can brand their AI as "Lab Insights by [Lab Name]" — fully white-labelled, no reference to OpenAI or Anthropic in any patient-facing UI.

### Consent Logging

`ai_usage_logs.consent_at` records the exact timestamp of patient consent before AI analysis runs. Combined with `provider` and `model`, this creates an immutable per-call consent audit trail — essential for regulatory compliance in healthcare contexts.

### Patient 2FA (not just users)

The `patients` table has its own independent 2FA implementation:

```sql
`two_factor_code`       varchar(191),    -- OTP code
`two_factor_expires_at` timestamp,
`google2fa_secret`      varchar(191),    -- TOTP secret
`google2fa_enabled`     tinyint(1),
`two_factor_type`       varchar(191)     -- 'email' or 'whatsapp'
```

Patient 2 (Ibrahim Adegoke) has `google2fa_enabled = 1` and `two_factor_type = 'whatsapp'` — confirming the WhatsApp 2FA channel is live in production, not just designed.

